## And Then This Week

Last week, Anthropic published ["Trustworthy Agents in Practice"](https://www.anthropic.com/research/trustworthy-agents)
— a research post defining a four-component agent architecture. Component #2:
"a harness — instructions and guardrails." Five core principles: keeping humans
in control, securing agent interactions, maintaining transparency, protecting
privacy. They described what a trustworthy agent system should look like.

We were already building it. Warden, Sentinel, Gate, trust tiers, config-driven
RBAC, OTEL tracing, PII filtering, memory scoping — that's the harness Anthropic
described, fully realized.

Then this morning, I saw the Hyperagents paper on arXiv (2603.19461). Meta
FAIR — self-referential agents that can modify their own improvement mechanisms.
I dropped it into Claude Code alongside this repo.

The first thing Claude said was: *"This maps directly onto the architecture
we've been designing"* — referring to the agents workflow/graph for self-improvement
of the codebase.

Here's the honest timeline:

In **January 2026** — nine weeks before HyperAgents was published — I shipped
CoinSwarm: a biological-evolution-inspired trading swarm where agent populations
self-improve through fitness-scored selection, mutation, crossover, ELO-rated
head-to-head competition, trio voting, and memory reinforcement. Agents that
perform well reproduce. Agents that fail die. The population gets smarter
through evaluation pressure. 620-line evolution engine, 660-line fitness
evaluator, 548-line memory system with reinforce/contradict/decay, 722-line
ELO system. All against live exchange data with real money at stake.

In **February 2026** — four weeks before HyperAgents — Maistro's trace
reviewer had an agent reviewing another agent's execution traces and producing
structured corrections. The Auditor/Mason pattern before those names existed.

In **April 2026** — two weeks after HyperAgents was published, but before I
knew it existed — Stronghold's feedback module shipped. The Auditor reviews
Mason's PRs, extracts learnings, stores corrections in agent memory, tracks
whether violations are decreasing.

I discovered the HyperAgents paper on **April 16, 2026**. That's when the
self-referential framing clicked — the improvement mechanism modifying itself.
That specific insight came from reading the paper. I won't claim otherwise.

But the core idea — agents should evaluate and improve other agents through
structured feedback — I arrived at independently, through building systems
where failure costs real money. CoinSwarm's fitness loops are not a research
prototype. They're connected to 7 exchange APIs. The 7-tier memory with
unforgettable regrets exists because a trading swarm that forgets a catastrophic
loss will repeat it.

We're calling it RASO: Reflexive Agentic Self-Optimization. The feedback loop
is primarily agent-driven — tournament scoring, learning extraction, automated
quality gates — but human feedback is welcome. Leave a comment on the PR and it
gets integrated into the next cycle. The system doesn't require human feedback
to improve, but it doesn't refuse it either. "Naive RLHF" was the old internal
name, but the "H" was misleading — the humans are optional participants, not
mandatory reviewers. RASO is what it actually is.

Last week, Anthropic described the harness. This week, Meta published the math
for self-improvement. The git history shows I was already building both.

---

Built with security-first design, a lot of late nights, and one agent that
named itself.

— Blake
